A fish-eye lens might be a bit too much for a birdhouse.
One learns from one's mistakes.
I should have known, since I've already made one with a "normal" lens.
I'll tell you more this weekend when I've installed the second one I've made.
Let's say that birds will have better Internet connectivity than mine in 2015.
Or at least, that's the goal.
The box that already contains a nesting box benefits from the house's Wi-Fi.
There's still work to be done to connect the other.
Well, I hung the other nesting box during the day. Here's how it looks in place in the garden.
But, little flashback: "What's inside?" don't I hear ask.
At the top is one of these ESP32 modules with a fish-eye lens camera and an infrared LED that I scavenged from a Raspberry Pi device.
If this plastic box has an odd shape, it's because of the pivoting side panel of the birdhouse. I bought it like this and couldn't modify it, so I had to design my installation around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the system is powered by a solar panel and a 18650 cell with a capacity of 2600 mAh.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a photo of the solar panel.
The gray box suspended next to the birdhouse houses the battery.
At full charge, it gives me about 4 hours of power.
I call it a feature. So the birds can have a little bit of privacy too.
At first, I wasn't sure if the Internet connection in our garden would be strong enough for this installation. The old access points I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been sufficient.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to mount a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and aim it downwards towards the garden.
I could still do it when I install more camera birdhouses, especially in areas far from the house, I might need it.
Now, for reasons that escape me for the moment, the camera is offline. It turned off barely an hour after sunset.
The battery charge may have stopped three hours before sunset due to a lack of light.
Maybe it didn't fully charge in just under half a day.
I'll see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have a battery telemetry system. I might add one during a future revision.
A few more sensors would be good, I think.
And maybe a battery capable of lasting all night, at least on paper.
Oh, and another lens.
The fish-eye is way too much.
But I'm already looking at components on Digikey, so I might just get a custom PCB for this use.
Or not. We'll see.
And, it is still offline.
Super.
Given the sun's position due to the solar panels installed on the house, it's really high for only about 90 minutes.
Let's wait another hour or two to see what happens or not.
Still offline.
Nothing is ever simple.
In fact, on the USB-C plate I was using to connect the battery charger, the 5V and ground were reversed.
I swapped the wires, and now I have a charging indicator.
The ESP did not connect right away, let's wait a few minutes.
One hour later: still offline.
It seems to be restarting in a loop and triggering Tasmota's reset functionality.
I think the panel is just shit. I ordered a bigger one, hoping it will work.
Check out what I found in the workshop.
A 24V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is so low (and partly hidden behind a tree) that it drops almost to nothing as soon as I use it.
I think I'll wait until tomorrow to see if this is sufficient for the installation or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it should generate up to 12V at a maximum of 1.2A.
So, either something is wrong with this panel or with my multimeter, or they have changed the specifications.
Good news, everyone!
They have changed the specifications and this one is defective.
The titles of the old and new specifications mention a 12V, 10W panel.
That's why I don't delete my old emails.
Hey, check it out: the thing reconnected for about a minute about an hour ago.
Maybe the panel charged the battery just enough for 38 seconds of power. It would have only taken a bit over two hours.
Guess what: it's cloudy today. So I'm not sure that this solar panel (probably broken) is capable of generating enough energy to do anything.
Let's see.
Latest news: I installed the new panel and it seems to be working.
If it turns out everything will turn off at sunset, but let's see.
By the way, I use the ping integration in Home Assistant to check if it's connected or not.
The round-trip time is 102 ms. Not great, but not so bad.
